article.headline: Golden Hurricane bounce back from loss to Kansas
article.linkText: Tulsa pulls away late, holds off Southwest Missouri St.
article.story:
SPRINGFIELD, Mo. (AP) -- Tulsa forward Kevin Johnson sounded like
a coach after the Golden Hurricane's victory over Southwest
Missouri State.

	   ''We didn't have the team consistency here,'' said Johnson, who
had 16 points, 12 rebounds and three blocked shots in Tulsa's 62-46
victory Saturday night.

	   ''We were trying to play individual ball, but we've got to work
together. ... Everybody has got to step up. We're going to be a
target, and teams are going to play hard and be prepared for us.''

	   Johnson had 10 points in the second half.

	   ''He really delivered for us, as he has done so many times,''
Tulsa coach John Phillips said.

	   Southwest Missouri (2-4) closed to 38-36 with 8:07 remaining,
but Tulsa (No. 18 ESPN/USA Today, No. 17 AP) pulled away with a 24-10 game-ending run.

	   Johnson sparked Tulsa (5-1) early in the second half with two straight
baskets, but Southwest Missouri's Shelton Colwell countered with
three straight field goals to get the Bears to 34-28.

	   But poor shooting by Southwest Missouri -- 31.5 percent on
18-for-54 from the field, including 0-for-14 for the 3-point range
-- made it almost impossible for the Bears to stay with Tulsa.

	   ''I thought the key to the game was we were 40-36 and we missed
six straight free throws,'' Southwest Missouri coach Barry Hinson
said. ''I can't explain the 0-for-14. I just can't. We played a
good game. We held the 17th-ranked team in the country to 62
points.''

	   Hinson, an Oklahoma product who has never beaten Tulsa in four
tries, was cut on the left cornea late in the game when he collided
with one of the referees. He continued to coach the rest of the
game.

	   Jason Parker added 13 points for Tulsa, and Jarius Glenn had 12.
Monwell Randle led Southwest Missouri with 17 points.

	   ''You play a Top 25 team and you play them that close. To let it
slip away, it just hurts a lot,'' Randle said.
